# Backend NestJS Rules

This rule applies to backend TypeScript files under `applications/backend`.
Use it with existing global DI, architecture, and code-convention rules.

## 1) Module Shape (mandatory)

Each feature module must follow this structure:

```
modules/<feature>/
├── application/
│   └── usecases/
├── domain/
│   ├── entities/
│   ├── ports/
│   └── tokens.ts
├── infrastructure/
│   ├── adapters/
│   └── dto/
├── <feature>.controller.ts
└── <feature>.module.ts
```

- Do not create a `controllers/` folder.
- Keep controllers at `modules/<feature>/`.
- Do not use `*.service.ts` for business logic.

## 2) Layer Responsibilities (mandatory)

- Controllers are input adapters only.
- Controllers call use cases only (never repositories/adapters directly).
- Controllers must avoid conditional business branching (`if/else`) on use case results.
- Controllers should delegate directly to `execute(...)` and let use cases throw domain/HTTP exceptions.
- Use cases hold business orchestration logic.
- Domain remains infrastructure-agnostic.
- Infrastructure adapters implement domain/application ports.

## 3) SRP and ISP (mandatory)

- One use case = one business intent.
- Do not create catch-all use cases (`*Crud*`, `Manage*`, `Save*`).
- Split ports by responsibility; avoid large mixed interfaces.
- Prefer explicit read/write separation when useful:
  - `I*ReadQuery.port.ts` (or `I*Query.port.ts`) for reads
  - `I*WriteRepository.port.ts` (or `I*Repository.port.ts`) for writes

## 4) Naming and Imports (mandatory)

- Use case files: `<Name>.usecase.ts` (example: `CreateCronjobK8s.usecase.ts`)
- Port files: `I*.port.ts`
- Adapter files: `*.adapter.ts`
- Internal imports must use `@src/...` alias (no deep relative imports).

## 5) Dependency Injection (mandatory)

- Define module tokens in `domain/tokens.ts`.
- Use symbol tokens for injected dependencies.
- Use explicit `@Inject(token)` in constructors where dependencies are wired by token.
- In controllers, inject use cases (not adapters/repositories).

## 6) Errors, Logging, and Tests (mandatory)

- Throw Nest exceptions (`BadRequestException`, `NotFoundException`, etc.).
- Do not mask known HTTP exceptions as generic 500 errors.
- Log unexpected errors with actionable context.
- Add unit tests for controllers and use cases when behavior changes.

## 7) CRUD Consistency (mandatory)

- Keep CRUD endpoint method names consistent: `getAll`, `get`, `create`, `update`, `delete`.
- `get`/`update` use cases must throw `NotFoundException` when target does not exist.
- For `@HttpCode(204)` delete endpoints, return `Promise<void>` from controller and use case.
